  "source": "Numerics/Data/Statistics/RunningStatistics.cs; expected values scraped verbatim from Test_RunningStatistics.cs (Test_Stats/Test_PopStats), which construct a RunningStatistics from the same 69-value sample used by fixtures/special_functions/percentile.json and validate each property to a 1e-10 delta against the values from Test_Statistics.cs. The `combined_*` cases scrape Test_Combine/Test_Add verbatim, which split the SAME 69-value sample into a 48-value sub-sample and a 21-value sub-sample, build a RunningStatistics from each, merge them via `RunningStatistics.Combine`/`operator+`, and assert the merge reproduces the exact same 8 values as Test_Stats/Test_PopStats above (min/max/mean/variance/sd/coefficient_of_variation/skewness/kurtosis) -- i.e. the C# tests themselves prove combine() is associative-with-single-pass on this data, so the expected values are identical to their un-combined counterparts by construction. The `clone_*` and `combined_with_*_empty`/`combined_both_empty` cases are adapted from the new v2.1.4 Test_Clone/Test_Combine_WithEmpty.",
  "reference": "Numerics @ 2a0357a. Not called out in the task brief's own fixture list, but added because the task's stated goal is that every ported prerequisite be oracle-validated before a sampler consumes it (ARWMH/Bootstrap both use RunningStatistics). Args convention: args = the flat sample (RunningStatistics's list constructor pushes every element in order); each dispatch target reads one property off the resulting instance. minimum/maximum/count are trivial (min/max of a fixed sample; N=69) but included for completeness of the ported member set. The `combined_*` targets close a gap: `RunningStatistics::combine()`/`operator+` had zero fixture coverage from the cases above (which only ever construct via the list ctor, never combine two instances). They use a DIFFERENT args convention: `[n1, sample1(n1 values), sample2(remaining values)]`, a 'split-index' convention rather than Correlation's equal-length two-halves split (Test_Combine/Test_Add's 48/21 sub-samples are unequal, so a fixed midpoint doesn't apply). Each `combined_*` dispatch target builds `RunningStatistics(sample1) + RunningStatistics(sample2)` (operator+, which forwards to the static `combine()` -- exercising both) and reads one property off the merged result. v2.1.4 added `Clone()` and changed `Combine` to return a clone (not a bare reference) when either operand is empty -- see running_statistics.hpp's file header: this was never observable in the C++ port (value semantics already gave an independent copy), so `clone_*`/`combined_with_*_empty` are additive coverage for the new API surface, not a re-pin. `clone_*` reuses the plain per-property targets' own `mean`/`combined_kurtosis` args convention (the flat sample) but reads the property off `RunningStatistics(sample).Clone()`; `combined_with_first_empty`/`combined_with_second_empty` reuse the EXISTING `combined_*` targets and args convention with `n1 = 0` (first operand empty) or `n1 = 69` (second operand empty, i.e. no args left after the sample) -- no new dispatch needed for those two since RunningStatisticsCombined()/running_statistics_combined() already handle an empty half correctly; `combined_both_empty` is the new `combined_count` target with `args = [0]` (both operands empty). See fixtures/README.md.",
